Title: What constitutes a useful restaurant review?

Geoffrey Anderson
November 20, 2015

Sorry, what was the question again?

Q: On the Yelp app, what is causing people to upvote some reviews as being “useful”?

So, I wrote this program in R language and my program uses a machine learning algorithm. I sent my program to go into the Yelp Challenge 2015 dataset to find out how to get upvoted. The program does text mining and topic clustering on the Yelp reviews using Latent Dirichlet Allocation and the main algorithm is a Generalized Boosting Machine with 150 trees and it trains on data with K-fold cross-validation, to learn what reviews get upvotes. The program went in, it saw, it learned, and then it told me….

Three things: 1.Be funny 2.Be wordy and ...

My program learned to predict which reviews got upvoted with 72% accuracy. Anyone can guess the answer at a base rate accuracy of 56% by just assuming useful==FALSE (0 upvotes). It proved to me that it learned something because I tested it by showing it a review it had never seen before. Before I let it see the data, I had secretly held back some data from it, so I still had some that it had never seen before. I covered up the upvotes on this unseen data. And 72% of the time it got it right.

My program told me that it is not WHAT you say, but HOW you say it.

We get by with a little help...

…from our friends! It is true.

>12 funny >1100 chars >125 friends = USEFUL REVIEW
